Restore the keyboard backlight brightness across suspend/resume.

On Samsung Galaxy Book models the firmware/EC resets the keyboard backlight
to off while the system is suspended. The samsung-galaxybook driver registers
the backlight as an LED class device but does not opt into the LED core's
built-in suspend/resume save+restore mechanism, and the platform driver has
no PM callbacks, so the user's brightness level is lost on resume.

The LED core's led_suspend()/led_resume() handlers (drivers/leds/led-class.c)
are gated entirely on the LED_CORE_SUSPENDRESUME flag. Setting it makes the
core save led_cdev->brightness on suspend and re-apply it on resume via the
driver's brightness_set_blocking op (kbd_backlight_acpi_set). Both software
writes and Fn+F9 hardware cycling update led_cdev->brightness (the latter via
led_set_brightness_sync), so the restored level is always correct.

Original samsung-galaxybook driver author: Joshua Grisham <josh@joshuagrisham.com>
Original project/research repo: https://github.com/joshuagrisham/samsung-galaxybook-extras
Upstream Linux driver source: drivers/platform/x86/samsung-galaxybook.c

--- samsung-galaxybook.c.orig
+++ samsung-galaxybook.c
@@ -388,7 +388,7 @@ static int galaxybook_kbd_backlight_init(struct samsung_galaxybook *galaxybook)
 
 	galaxybook->kbd_backlight.brightness_get = kbd_backlight_show;
 	galaxybook->kbd_backlight.brightness_set_blocking = kbd_backlight_store;
-	galaxybook->kbd_backlight.flags = LED_BRIGHT_HW_CHANGED;
+	galaxybook->kbd_backlight.flags = LED_BRIGHT_HW_CHANGED | LED_CORE_SUSPENDRESUME;
 	galaxybook->kbd_backlight.max_brightness = GB_KBD_BACKLIGHT_MAX_BRIGHTNESS;
 
 	return devm_led_classdev_register_ext(&galaxybook->platform->dev,
